content.description: Stiffish start followed by fun movement and cool holds to a head-scratching finish.
content.location: Very near the center of the cliff.  Starts 10 feet or so right of the BIG detached flake.

content.description: Moderate but fun start steepens as you go. Last bit can be done going left (5.8 ?) or straight up (5.9 ?). Going left is a bit more committing due to sideways fall potential, but it's your choice.  Perhaps a touch spicey either way if you are at your limit.Probably my last FA and last outdoor route for the year..... :(
content.location: far left side of players club.

climbs.name: If a Slip Don't Get You Then The Virus Will

content.description: Easy climbing leads you to a short left facing corner left of the black stain and bulge. At the top a few moves right lead to a powerful move or two into a shallow corner. The end is a test of your balancing skills. Top-roped and cleaned up the finish before doing the FA then added the bolts.
content.location: Climb main weakness to the tallest point on the cliff.

content.description: Stiff start that tickles 5.10. Then up bulge to put right hand in horizontal hueco. Feet disappear so jump up into a high step to do upper crux.  Then cruise to anchor. Pretty thoughtful all the way.
content.location: 3rd route from right. Goes up to left side of big horizontal hueco.

content.description: Line was spied by jojo. I wasn't sure it looked worthwhile, but his eye was true.Fun, full-pad crimping leads to an easy section and good rest. Then a hard-to-read (?) crux over a small roof.  Easy to anchor. There is a loose-looking block to the right of the route. I tried to pry it off with a small crowbar but couldnt budge it.Crux is easier to read now that there is a bolt to direct your attention.
content.location: Starts a few feet right of the big, fragile-looking, detached flake at bottom center of crag.

climbs.name: Free Coronas
climbs.fa: Rebecca Johnstone, Charles Brands, Alison Elder, JBak, Mar 2020

content.description: Has some cool holds. Fairly sustained through its short length.
content.protection: 4 bolts and a steel biner anchor.

content.description: Start up a big flake being a little careful at the top. The first challenge comes fast but the real difficulty is the bulge in the black stain.
content.protection: 8 bolts and steel carabiner lower offs

content.description: Fun face climbing up to the right side of a horizontal hueco.
content.location: 2nd route from right side of crag.  Goes up to right side of big horizontal hueco, and then up to just right of big prickly pear at top of cliff.

content.description: A decent route that steepens and builds as you go.
content.location: 2nd route from left. Tallest route at crag.

content.description:
Lower angle crag with potential for some moderates. Routes will range from 30 to 60 feet. All of the routes have surprised me with their goodness.

 Morning sun if you are cold.  Afternoon shade if you are hot.  Further from road so less road noise.

 Josie wandered up here while I was doing some work at High Stakes.  She said "There's a little crag up there that doesn't look too bad.  You should go take a look."
